{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656141"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:10:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18714"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18714"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.81,0.05,0,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77043"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11446"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62549"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"10646"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26509"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77043"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe mammary ductal system forms an essential transport network connecting milk-producing alveoli to the nipple during lactation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the structure and function of mammary ducts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Simple squamous epithelium with smooth muscle layers","Cuboidal epithelium with surrounding myoepithelial cells","Stratified epithelium with elastic tissue","Columnar epithelium with dense connective tissue","Transitional epithelium with contractile fibres"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct structure involves \u003Cstrong\u003Ecuboidal epithelium with surrounding myoepithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E. The ductal epithelium is primarily cuboidal, and the myoepithelial cells provide contractile function necessary for milk transport when stimulated by oxytocin during the let-down reflex.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple squamous epithelium with smooth muscle layers\u003C/strong\u003E - Squamous epithelium would not provide the necessary secretory and transport functions\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStratified epithelium with elastic tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - The ducts are lined by simple, not stratified epithelium\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColumnar epithelium with dense connective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - While some larger ducts may have columnar cells, the majority are cuboidal\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransitional epithelium with contractile fibres\u003C/strong\u003E - Transitional epithelium is found in the urinary system, not mammary ducts\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe ductal system forms a branching network that begins at the alveoli and converges into 15-20 main ducts that open at the nipple. This arrangement allows for efficient milk collection and delivery during lactation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mammary ducts are lined with cuboidal epithelium and surrounded by myoepithelial cells that enable milk transport.","Milk ducts form a branching network that converges into 15-20 main ducts opening at the nipple.","The ductal system connects milk-producing alveoli to the nipple to enable infant feeding."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62549"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18714"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62549"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T23:05:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T23:06:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11446"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77043"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t